{"title_page": "Motor program", "text_new": "A '''motor program''' is an abstract representation of movement that centrally organizes and controls the many [[Degrees of freedom (mechanics)|degrees of freedom]] involved in performing an action.<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\">{{Cite book | last1 = Schmidt | first1 = Richard A. | last2 = Lee | first2 = Timothy Donald | title = Motor control and learning : a behavioral emphasis | year = 2005 | publisher = Human Kinetics | location = Champaign, IL | isbn = 978-0-7360-4258-1 | oclc = 265658315 | url = https://archive.org/details/motorcontrollear00schm }}</ref><sup>p.&nbsp;182</sup> Signals transmitted through [[efferent nerve fiber|efferent]] and [[afferent nerve fiber|afferent]] pathways allow the central nervous system to anticipate, plan or guide movement. Evidence for the concept of motor programs include the following:<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;182</sup>\n:# Processing of afferent information (feedback) is too slow for on-going regulation of rapid movements.\n:# Reaction time (time between \u201cgo\u201d signal and movement initiation) increases with movement complexity, suggesting that movements are planned in advance.\n:# Movement is possible even without feedback from the moving limb. Moreover, velocity and acceleration of feedforward movements such as reaching are highly proportional to the distance of the target. \n:# The existence of motor equivalence, i.e., the ability to perform the same action in multiple ways for instance using different muscles or the same muscles under different conditions. This suggests that a general code specifying the final output exists which is translated into specific muscle action sequences\n:# Brain activation precedes that of movement. For example, the supplementary motor area becomes active one second before voluntary movement.\n\nThis is not meant to underestimate the importance of feedback information, merely that another level of control beyond feedback is used:<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/>\n:# Before the movement as information about initial position, or perhaps to tune the spinal apparatus.\n:# During the movement, when it is either \u201cmonitored\u201d for the presence of error or used directly in the modulation of movements reflexively.\n:# After the movement to determine the success of the response and contribute to motor learning.\n\n== Central organization ==\n\n=== Open and closed-loop theories ===\n\n==== Response-chaining hypothesis ====\nThe response-chaining, or reflex-chaining hypothesis, proposed by William James (1890),<ref>{{cite book | last1 = James | first1 = William | title = Principles of psychology. | publisher = Dover Publications | date = 1890-c1918 | year = 1950 | location = New York | isbn = 9780486203812 | oclc = 191755 | url = https://archive.org/details/principlesofpsyc00will }}</ref> was one of the earliest descriptions of movement control. This open-loop hypothesis postulated that movements required attention only for initiation of the first action.<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;165</sup> As such, each subsequent movement was thought to be automatically triggered by response-produced afferent information from the muscles. Although feedback is involved in this process, ongoing movements cannot be modified if there are unexpected changes in the environment; feedback is not  compared to some internally generated reference value for error checking.  However, research involving deafferented animals<ref name=\"Taub 1975\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Taub E, Goldberg IA, Taub P |title=Deafferentation in monkeys: pointing at a target without visual feedback |journal=Exp. Neurol. |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=178\u201386 |date=January 1975 |pmid=1109336  |doi=10.1016/0014-4886(75)90040-0}}</ref> and humans<ref name=\"Rothwell 1982\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Rothwell JC, Traub MM, Day BL, Obeso JA, Thomas PK, Marsden CD |title=Manual motor performance in a deafferented man |journal=Brain |volume=105 |issue= 3|pages=515\u201342 |date=September 1982 |pmid=6286035 |doi=10.1093/brain/105.3.515|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c92578f04b6ad724270fe4c211b733826ee4033b }}</ref> suggests feedback is not necessary for movement, thus the response-chaining hypothesis provides an incomplete account of movement control.\n\n==== Adams\u2019 closed-loop theory ====\nIn contrast to the open-loop response-chaining hypothesis, Adams' closed-loop theory suggested that processing of afferent information was central in human motor control.<ref name=\"Adams 1971\">{{cite journal |author=Adams JA |title=A closed-loop theory of motor learning |journal=J mot Behav |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=111\u201349 |date=June 1971 |pmid=15155169 |doi=10.1080/00222895.1971.10734898 |url=}}</ref> Adams\u2019 closed-loop theory is based on basic motor learning research that focused on slow, graded, linear positioning tasks, which involved error detection and correction to meet goal demands. To learn a movement, a \u201cmotor program\u201d consisting of two states of memory (i.e. memory trace and perceptual trace), is required. The memory trace (equivalent to recall memory in verbal learning) initiates the motor movement, chooses its initial direction and determines the earliest portions of the movement. Strengthening of the memory trace results from practice and feedback about movement outcome (see motor learning). In addition, the perceptual trace (similar to recognition memory in verbal tasks) is involved in guidance of the limb to the correct position along a trajectory. This is accomplished by comparing incoming feedback to the perceptual trace, which is formed from the sensory consequences of the limb being at the correct/incorrect endpoint in past experience. In the event of an error, the limb is adjusted until the movement is appropriate to the goal of the action. Importantly, the more accurate the movement, the more useful the perceptual trace that is collected and retained.\n\nThough this theory represented an important leap forward in motor learning research,<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/> one weakness in Adams\u2019 closed-loop theory was the requirement of 1-to-1 mapping between stored states (motor programs) and movements to be made. This presented an issue related to the storage capacity of the central nervous system; a vast array of movements would require equally large repository of motor programs. Additionally, this theory could not be used to explain how motor programs for novel movements were formed.\n\n=== Schmidt\u2019s schema theory ===\n\nEarly motor program theories did not adequately account for  evidence illustrating the influence of feedback  for the modification of ongoing movement  while providing a suitable explanation of motor programs storage or application in novel movement. Consequently, the notion of the generalized motor program (GMP) was developed.<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;205</sup> The GMP is thought to contain an abstract representation for a class of movements with invariant features pertaining to the order of events, the relative timing of events and the relative force with which events are produced. In order to determine how a particular movement should be performed, parameters such as overall movement duration, overall force of contractions and the muscles involved are specified to the GMP. This revision of the motor program concept allows many different movements to be produced with the same motor program as well as the production of novel movements by specifying new parameters.\n\nRichard Schmidt (1975) proposed the schema theory for motor control,<ref name=\"Schmidt 1975\">{{cite journal|last1=Schmidt|first1=Richard A.|title=A schema theory of discrete motor skill learning.|journal=Psychological Review|volume=82| issue=4|year=1975| pages=225\u2013260| url=http://www.hp-research.com/sites/default/files/publications/Schmidt%20%28Psych%20Review,%201975%29.pdf|doi=10.1037/h0076770}}</ref> suggesting in opposition to closed-loop theories, that a motor program containing general rules can be applied to different environmental or situational contexts via the involvement of  open-loop control process and GMPs.<ref name=\"Shumway-Cook 2001\">{{Cite book  | last1 = Shumway-Cook | first1 = Anne | last2 = Woollacott | first2 = Marjorie H. | title = Motor control : theory and practical application | year = 2001 | publisher = Lippincott Williams Wilkins | location = Philadelphia | isbn = 978-0-683-30643-9 | oclc= 499223436 }}</ref><sup>p.&nbsp;32</sup> In Schmidt's theory, the [[schema (psychology)]] contains the generalized rules that generate the spatial and temporal muscle patterns to produce a specified movement.<ref name=\"Shumway-Cook 2001\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;32</sup> Therefore,  when learning novel movements an individual may generate  a new GMP based on the selection of parameters (reducing the novel movement problem), or refine an existing GMP (reducing the storage problem), depending on prior experience with movement and task context.\n\nAccording to Schmidt, four things are stored in memory after an individual generates a movement:<ref name=\"Schmidt 1975\"/>\n# The initial conditions of the movement, such as the proprioceptive information of the limbs and body.\n# The response specifications for the motor programs, which are the parameters used in the generalized motor program, such as speed and force.\n# The sensory consequences of the response, which contain information about how the movement felt, looked and sounded.\n# The outcome of that movement, which contains information of the actual outcome of the movement with knowledge of results (KR).\n\nThis information is stored in components of the motor response schema, which include the recall schema and recognition schema. The recall and recognition schema are strongly associated, as they use the relationship between the initial condition and actual outcomes; however, they are not isomorphic.<ref name=\"Schmidt 1975\"/> They differ  in that recall schema is used to select a specific response with the use of response specifications, whereas the recognition schema is used to evaluate the response with the sensory consequences. Throughout a movement, the recognition schema is compared to the expected sensory information (e.g., proprioceptive and extroceptive) from the ongoing movement to evaluate the efficiency of the response.<ref name=\"Shumway-Cook 2001\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;32</sup> An error signal is sent upon finalizing the movement, where the schema is then modified based on the sensory feedback and knowledge of results (see motor learning).\n\nThe schema theory illustrates that motor learning consists of continuous processes that update the recall and recognition schemas with each movement that is made.<ref name=\"Shumway-Cook 2001\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;33</sup>\n\n=== Multiple paired forward and inverse models ===\n\nAn alternate viewpoint on the organization and control of motor programs may be considered a computational process of selecting a motor command (i.e., the input) to achieve a desired sensory feedback (i.e., the output).<ref name=\"Wolpert 1998\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wolpert DM, Kawato M |title=Multiple paired forward and inverse models for motor control |journal=Neural Netw |volume=11 |issue=7\u20138 |pages=1317\u201329 |date=October 1998 |pmid=12662752 |doi=10.1016/S0893-6080(98)00066-5 |url=http://www.cns.atr.jp/~kawato/Ppdf/1217.pdf|citeseerx=10.1.1.36.4705 }}</ref> Selection of the motor command depends on many internal and external variables, such as the current state of the limb(s), orientation of the body and properties of the items in the environment with which the body will interact. Given the vast number of possible combinations of these variables, the motor control system must be able to provide an appropriate command for any given context. One strategy for selecting appropriate commands involves a modular approach; multiple controllers exist such that each controller is suitable for one or a small set of contexts. Based on an estimate of the current context, a controller is chosen to generate the appropriate motor command.\n\nThis modular system can be used to describe both motor control and [[motor learning]] and requires adaptable internal forward and inverse models.  Forward models describe the forward or causal relationship between system inputs, predicting sensory feedback that will occur. Inverse models (controllers) generate the motor command that will cause a desired change in state, given an environmental context. During motor learning, the forward and inverse models are paired and tightly coupled by a responsibility signal within modules. Using the forward model's predictions and sensory contextual cues, responsibility signals indicate the degree to which each pair should be responsible for controlling current behavior.\n\n== Impairment of motor programs ==\n\n=== Cerebellar degeneration ===\n\nErrors in reaching are commonly found in patients with cerebellar degeneration. This suggests their motor commands do not predicatively compensate for interaction torques inherent in multi-joint motion.<ref name=\"Bastian 1996\">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Bastian | first1 = AJ. | last2 = Martin | first2 = TA. | last3 = Keating | first3 = JG. | last4 = Thach | first4 = WT. | title = Cerebellar ataxia: abnormal control of interaction torques across multiple joints. | journal = J Neurophysiol | volume = 76 | issue = 1 | pages = 492\u2013509 |date=Jul 1996 | pmid = 8836239 | doi = 10.1152/jn.1996.76.1.492 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/08c7cd2aad071252919514d792b7cf64a98a5ace }}</ref><ref name=\"Bastian 2000\">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Bastian | first1 = AJ. | last2 = Zackowski | first2 = KM. | last3 = Thach | first3 = WT. | title = Cerebellar ataxia: torque deficiency or torque mismatch between joints? | journal = J Neurophysiol | volume = 83 | issue = 5 | pages = 3019\u201330 |date=May 2000 | pmid = 10805697 | doi = 10.1152/jn.2000.83.5.3019 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c86be191432db3abb56bf11c3050a7b62abeafcd }}</ref><ref name=\"Goodkin 1993\">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Goodkin | first1 = HP. | last2 = Keating | first2 = JG. | last3 = Martin | first3 = TA. | last4 = Thach | first4 = WT. | title = Preserved simple and impaired compound movement after infarction in the territory of the superior cerebellar artery. | journal = Can J Neurol Sci | volume = 20 Suppl 3 | issue =  | pages = S93\u2013104 |date=May 1993 | doi =  10.1017/s0317167100048599| pmid = 8334599 }}</ref><ref name=\"Topka 1998\">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Topka | first1 = H. | last2 = Konczak | first2 = J. | last3 = Schneider | first3 = K. | last4 = Boose | first4 = A. | last5 = Dichgans | first5 = J. | title = Multijoint arm movements in cerebellar ataxia: abnormal control of movement dynamics. | journal = Exp Brain Res | volume = 119 | issue = 4 | pages = 493\u2013503 |date=Apr 1998 | doi = 10.1007/s002210050365 | pmid = 9588784 }}</ref> Several lines of research have been conducted to understand this, with evidence being provided that this impairment may be due to a malfunctioning inverse model:\n* the cerebellum plays a dominant role in representing the inverse model<ref name=\"Kawato 1992\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kawato M, Gomi H |title=A computational model of four regions of the cerebellum based on feedback-error learning |journal=Biol Cybern |volume=68 |issue=2 |pages=95\u2013103 |year=1992 |pmid=1486143 |doi=10.1007/BF00201431 |url=}}</ref>\n* the cerebellum is active during learning of arm movements in force fields.<ref name=\"Nezafat 2001\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Nezafat R, Shadmehr R, Holcomb HH |title=Long-term adaptation to dynamics of reaching movements: a PET study |journal=Exp Brain Res |volume=140 |issue=1 |pages=66\u201376 |date=September 2001 |pmid=11500799 |doi=10.1007/s002210100787 |url=}}</ref>\n\nWith this knowledge, an experiment conducted by Smith and Shadmehr (2005)<ref name=\"Smith 2005\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Smith MA, Shadmehr R |title=Intact ability to learn internal models of arm dynamics in Huntington's disease but not cerebellar degeneration |journal=J. Neurophysiol. |volume=93 |issue=5 |pages=2809\u201321 |date=May 2005 |pmid=15625094 |doi=10.1152/jn.00943.2004 |url=|citeseerx=10.1.1.392.195 }}</ref> illustrated an impaired ability for cerebellar subjects to alter motor commands to compensate for applied force fields within a trial (i.e. modify an ongoing movement) as well as to use this error to update the following trial (i.e. changes in a following trial were unrelated to prior trial error). This agreed with prior work by Mascheke et al. (2004)<ref name=\"Maschke 2003\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Maschke M, Gomez CM, Ebner TJ, Konczak J |title=Hereditary cerebellar ataxia progressively impairs force adaptation during goal-directed arm movements |journal=J. Neurophysiol. |volume=91 |issue=1 |pages=230\u20138 |date=January 2004 |pmid=13679403 |doi=10.1152/jn.00557.2003 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/2415d3a19b241d4a2d3775d79ad20f4345d8534f}}</ref> who illustrated those with cerebellar degeneration had difficulty adapting motor commands when limb dynamics were altered.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Central pattern generator]]\n*[[Challenge Point Framework]]\n*[[Hearing (sense)|Hearing]]\n*[[Multisensory integration]]\n*[[Proprioception]]\n*[[Vestibular system]]\n*[[Visual perception]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading ==\n\n=== Sensory contributions to motor control ===\n# {{cite journal |author=Bastian AJ |title=Understanding sensorimotor adaptation and learning for rehabilitation |journal=Curr. Opin. Neurol. |volume=21 |issue=6 |pages=628\u201333 |date=December 2008 |pmid=18989103 |pmc=2954436 |doi=10.1097/WCO.0b013e328315a293 |url=}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Bent LR, McFadyen BJ, Inglis JT |title=Vestibular contributions during human locomotor tasks |journal=Exerc Sport Sci Rev |volume=33 |issue=3 |pages=107\u201313 |date=July 2005 |pmid=16006817 |doi= 10.1097/00003677-200507000-00002}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Chapman GJ, Hollands MA |title=Age-related differences in stepping performance during step cycle-related removal of vision |journal=Exp Brain Res |volume=174 |issue=4 |pages=613\u201321 |date=October 2006 |pmid=16733708 |doi=10.1007/s00221-006-0507-6 |url=}}\n# {{cite book | last1 = Elliott | first1 = D | title = Intermittent versus continuous control of manual aiming movements | editors = L Proteau; D Elliott | work = Vision and Motor Control. Advances in Psychology, Volume 85 |pages = 33\u201348| publisher = Elsevier Science & Technology |location = New York | year = 1992 | isbn = 9781281789396 |oclc = 742292994}} \n# {{Cite book  | last1 = Kandel | first1 = Eric R. | title = Principles of Neural Science | year = 2012 | publisher = McGraw-Hill | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-07-139011-8 | oclc = 795553723 }}\n# {{Cite book  | last1 = Latash | first1 = Mark L. | title = Neurophysiological basis of movement | year = 2008 | publisher = Human Kinetics | location = Champaign, IL | isbn = 978-0-7360-6367-8 | oclc =  175174377 }}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Perry SD, McIlroy WE, Maki BE |title=The role of plantar cutaneous mechanoreceptors in the control of compensatory stepping reactions evoked by unpredictable, multi-directional perturbation |journal=Brain Res. |volume=877 |issue=2 |pages=401\u20136 |date=September 2000 |pmid=10986360 |doi=10.1016/S0006-8993(00)02712-8 |url=}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Reynolds RF, Day BL |title=Visual guidance of the human foot during a step |journal=J. Physiol. |volume=569 |issue=Pt 2 |pages=677\u201384 |date=December 2005 |pmid=16179363 |pmc=1464243 |doi=10.1113/jphysiol.2005.095869 |url=}}\n\n=== Control of Movement ===\n#{{Cite book  | last1 = Schmidt | first1 = Richard A. | last2 = Lee | first2 = Timothy Donald | title = Motor control and learning : a behavioral emphasis | year = 2011 | publisher = Human Kinetics | location = Champaign, IL | isbn = 978-0-7360-7961-7 | oclc = 814261802}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Grillner S, Wall\u00e9n P, Saitoh K, Kozlov A, Robertson B |title=Neural bases of goal-directed locomotion in vertebrates--an overview |journal=Brain Res Rev |volume=57 |issue=1 |pages=2\u201312 |date=January 2008 |pmid=17916382 |doi=10.1016/j.brainresrev.2007.06.027 |url=}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Marder E, Calabrese RL |title=Principles of rhythmic motor pattern generation |journal=Physiol. Rev. |volume=76 |issue=3 |pages=687\u2013717 |date=July 1996 |pmid=8757786 |doi= 10.1152/physrev.1996.76.3.687|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/19008ec50b0d0bcff24438c9a0eb57f9e33f7a85 }}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Shik ML, Orlovski\u012d GN, Severin FV |title=[Locomotion of the mesencephalic cat evoked by pyramidal stimulation] |language=Russian |journal=Biofizika |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=127\u201335 |year=1968 |pmid=5660863 |doi= |url=}}\n\n'''Reflexive, Triggered, and Voluntary Movement'''\n#  {{cite book | last1 = Rothwell | first1 = John C. | title = Control of Human Voluntary Movement | publisher = Chapman & Hall | year = 1994 | location = London | isbn = 978-0412477003 |oclc = 613884041 }}\n\n'''Speed, Accuracy, Movement Complexity'''\n# {{cite journal|last1=Fitts|first1=Paul M.|title=The information capacity of the human motor system in controlling the amplitude of movement.|journal=Journal of Experimental Psychology: General| volume=121|issue=3|year=1992|pages=262\u2013269|doi=10.1037/0096-3445.121.3.262|pmid=1402698|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/35f693753e23f5cda54815a55871fadc62cf18b3}}\n# {{cite journal|last1=Hick|first1=W. E.|title=On the rate of gain of information|journal=Quarterly Journal of Experimental Psychology|volume=4| issue=1|year=1952| pages=11\u201326| doi=10.1080/17470215208416600|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ee7363ba39bfc3dd030844933375d7585c7c9b66}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Dassonville P, Lewis SM, Foster HE, Ashe J |title=Choice and stimulus-response compatibility affect duration of response selection |journal=Brain Res Cogn Brain Res |volume=7 |issue=3 |pages=235\u201340 |date=January 1999 |pmid=9838139 |doi=10.1016/s0926-6410(98)00027-5}}\n# {{cite journal |author=Favilla M |title=Reaching movements: programming time course is independent of choice number |journal=NeuroReport |volume=7 |issue=15\u201317 |pages=2629\u201334 |date=November 1996 |pmid=8981436 |doi=10.1097/00001756-199611040-00044}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n[[Category:Motor system]]\n[[Category:Motor skills]]\n[[Category:Motor control]]\n", "text_old": "A '''motor program''' is an abstract representation of movement that centrally organizes and controls the many [[Degrees of freedom (mechanics)|degrees of freedom]] involved in performing an action.<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\">{{Cite book | last1 = Schmidt | first1 = Richard A. | last2 = Lee | first2 = Timothy Donald | title = Motor control and learning : a behavioral emphasis | year = 2005 | publisher = Human Kinetics | location = Champaign, IL | isbn = 978-0-7360-4258-1 | oclc = 265658315 | url = https://archive.org/details/motorcontrollear00schm }}</ref><sup>p.&nbsp;182</sup> Signals transmitted through [[efferent nerve fiber|efferent]] and [[afferent nerve fiber|afferent]] pathways allow the central nervous system to anticipate, plan or guide movement. Evidence for the concept of motor programs include the following:<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;182</sup>\n:# Processing of afferent information (feedback) is too slow for on-going regulation of rapid movements.\n:# Reaction time (time between \u201cgo\u201d signal and movement initiation) increases with movement complexity, suggesting that movements are planned in advance.\n:# Movement is possible even without feedback from the moving limb. Moreover, velocity and acceleration of feedforward movements such as reaching are highly proportional to the distance of the target. \n:# The existence of motor equivalence, i.e., the ability to perform the same action in multiple ways for instance using different muscles or the same muscles under different conditions. This suggests that a general code specifying the final output exists which is translated into specific muscle action sequences\n:# Brain activation precedes that of movement. For example, the supplementary motor area becomes active one second before voluntary movement.\n\nThis is not meant to underestimate the importance of feedback information, merely that another level of control beyond feedback is used:<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/>\n:# Before the movement as information about initial position, or perhaps to tune the spinal apparatus.\n:# During the movement, when it is either \u201cmonitored\u201d for the presence of error or used directly in the modulation of movements reflexively.\n:# After the movement to determine the success of the response and contribute to motor learning.\n\n== Central organization ==\n\n=== Open and closed-loop theories ===\n\n==== Response-chaining hypothesis ====\nThe response-chaining, or reflex-chaining hypothesis, proposed by William James (1890),<ref>{{cite book | last1 = James | first1 = William | title = Principles of psychology. | publisher = Dover Publications | date = 1890-c1918 | year = 1950 | location = New York | isbn = 9780486203812 | oclc = 191755 | url = https://archive.org/details/principlesofpsyc00will }}</ref> was one of the earliest descriptions of movement control. This open-loop hypothesis postulated that movements required attention only for initiation of the first action.<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;165</sup> As such, each subsequent movement was thought to be automatically triggered by response-produced afferent information from the muscles. Although feedback is involved in this process, ongoing movements cannot be modified if there are unexpected changes in the environment; feedback is not  compared to some internally generated reference value for error checking.  However, research involving deafferented animals<ref name=\"Taub 1975\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Taub E, Goldberg IA, Taub P |title=Deafferentation in monkeys: pointing at a target without visual feedback |journal=Exp. Neurol. |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=178\u201386 |date=January 1975 |pmid=1109336  |doi=10.1016/0014-4886(75)90040-0}}</ref> and humans<ref name=\"Rothwell 1982\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Rothwell JC, Traub MM, Day BL, Obeso JA, Thomas PK, Marsden CD |title=Manual motor performance in a deafferented man |journal=Brain |volume=105 |issue= 3|pages=515\u201342 |date=September 1982 |pmid=6286035 |doi=10.1093/brain/105.3.515|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c92578f04b6ad724270fe4c211b733826ee4033b }}</ref> suggests feedback is not necessary for movement, thus the response-chaining hypothesis provides an incomplete account of movement control.\n\n==== Adams\u2019 closed-loop theory ====\nIn contrast to the open-loop response-chaining hypothesis, Adams' closed-loop theory suggested that processing of afferent information was central in human motor control.<ref name=\"Adams 1971\">{{cite journal |author=Adams JA |title=A closed-loop theory of motor learning |journal=J mot Behav |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=111\u201349 |date=June 1971 |pmid=15155169 |doi=10.1080/00222895.1971.10734898 |url=}}</ref> Adams\u2019 closed-loop theory is based on basic motor learning research that focused on slow, graded, linear positioning tasks, which involved error detection and correction to meet goal demands. To learn a movement, a \u201cmotor program\u201d consisting of two states of memory (i.e. memory trace and perceptual trace), is required. The memory trace (equivalent to recall memory in verbal learning) initiates the motor movement, chooses its initial direction and determines the earliest portions of the movement. Strengthening of the memory trace results from practice and feedback about movement outcome (see motor learning). In addition, the perceptual trace (similar to recognition memory in verbal tasks) is involved in guidance of the limb to the correct position along a trajectory. This is accomplished by comparing incoming feedback to the perceptual trace, which is formed from the sensory consequences of the limb being at the correct/incorrect endpoint in past experience. In the event of an error, the limb is adjusted until the movement is appropriate to the goal of the action. Importantly, the more accurate the movement, the more useful the perceptual trace that is collected and retained.\n\nThough this theory represented an important leap forward in motor learning research,<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/> one weakness in Adams\u2019 closed-loop theory was the requirement of 1-to-1 mapping between stored states (motor programs) and movements to be made. This presented an issue related to the storage capacity of the central nervous system; a vast array of movements would require equally large repository of motor programs. Additionally, this theory could not be used to explain how motor programs for novel movements were formed.\n\n=== Schmidt\u2019s schema theory ===\n\nEarly motor program theories did not adequately account for  evidence illustrating the influence of feedback  for the modification of ongoing movement  while providing a suitable explanation of motor programs storage or application in novel movement. Consequently, the notion of the generalized motor program (GMP) was developed.<ref name=\"Schmidt 2005\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;205</sup> The GMP is thought to contain an abstract representation for a class of movements with invariant features pertaining to the order of events, the relative timing of events and the relative force with which events are produced. In order to determine how a particular movement should be performed, parameters such as overall movement duration, overall force of contractions and the muscles involved are specified to the GMP. This revision of the motor program concept allows many different movements to be produced with the same motor program as well as the production of novel movements by specifying new parameters.\n\nRichard Schmidt (1975) proposed the schema theory for motor control,<ref name=\"Schmidt 1975\">{{cite journal|last1=Schmidt|first1=Richard A.|title=A schema theory of discrete motor skill learning.|journal=Psychological Review|volume=82| issue=4|year=1975| pages=225\u2013260| url=http://www.hp-research.com/sites/default/files/publications/Schmidt%20%28Psych%20Review,%201975%29.pdf|doi=10.1037/h0076770}}</ref> suggesting in opposition to closed-loop theories, that a motor program containing general rules can be applied to different environmental or situational contexts via the involvement of  open-loop control process and GMPs.<ref name=\"Shumway-Cook 2001\">{{Cite book  | last1 = Shumway-Cook | first1 = Anne | last2 = Woollacott | first2 = Marjorie H. | title = Motor control : theory and practical application | year = 2001 | publisher = Lippincott Williams Wilkins | location = Philadelphia | isbn = 978-0-683-30643-9 | oclc= 499223436 }}</ref><sup>p.&nbsp;32</sup> In Schmidt\u2019s theory, the [[schema (psychology)]] contains the generalized rules that generate the spatial and temporal muscle patterns to produce a specified movement.<ref name=\"Shumway-Cook 2001\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;32</sup> Therefore,  when learning novel movements an individual may generate  a new GMP based on the selection of parameters (reducing the novel movement problem), or refine an existing GMP (reducing the storage problem), depending on prior experience with movement and task context.\n\nAccording to Schmidt, four things are stored in memory after an individual generates a movement:<ref name=\"Schmidt 1975\"/>\n# The initial conditions of the movement, such as the proprioceptive information of the limbs and body.\n# The response specifications for the motor programs, which are the parameters used in the generalized motor program, such as speed and force.\n# The sensory consequences of the response, which contain information about how the movement felt, looked and sounded.\n# The outcome of that movement, which contains information of the actual outcome of the movement with knowledge of results (KR).\n\nThis information is stored in components of the motor response schema, which include the recall schema and recognition schema. The recall and recognition schema are strongly associated, as they use the relationship between the initial condition and actual outcomes; however, they are not isomorphic.<ref name=\"Schmidt 1975\"/> They differ  in that recall schema is used to select a specific response with the use of response specifications, whereas the recognition schema is used to evaluate the response with the sensory consequences. Throughout a movement, the recognition schema is compared to the expected sensory information (e.g., proprioceptive and extroceptive) from the ongoing movement to evaluate the efficiency of the response.<ref name=\"Shumway-Cook 2001\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;32</sup> An error signal is sent upon finalizing the movement, where the schema is then modified based on the sensory feedback and knowledge of results (see motor learning).\n\nThe schema theory illustrates that motor learning consists of continuous processes that update the recall and recognition schemas with each movement that is made.<ref name=\"Shumway-Cook 2001\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;33</sup>\n\n=== Multiple paired forward and inverse models ===\n\nAn alternate viewpoint on the organization and control of motor programs may be considered a computational process of selecting a motor command (i.e., the input) to achieve a desired sensory feedback (i.e., the output).<ref name=\"Wolpert 1998\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wolpert DM, Kawato M |title=Multiple paired forward and inverse models for motor control |journal=Neural Netw |volume=11 |issue=7\u20138 |pages=1317\u201329 |date=October 1998 |pmid=12662752 |doi=10.1016/S0893-6080(98)00066-5 |url=http://www.cns.atr.jp/~kawato/Ppdf/1217.pdf|citeseerx=10.1.1.36.4705 }}</ref> Selection of the motor command depends on many internal and external variables, such as the current state of the limb(s), orientation of the body and properties of the items in the environment with which the body will interact. Given the vast number of possible combinations of these variables, the motor control system must be able to provide an appropriate command for any given context. One strategy for selecting appropriate commands involves a modular approach; multiple controllers exist such that each controller is suitable for one or a small set of contexts. Based on an estimate of the current context, a controller is chosen to generate the appropriate motor command.\n\nThis modular system can be used to describe both motor control and [[motor learning]] and requires adaptable internal forward and inverse models.  Forward models describe the forward or causal relationship between system inputs, predicting sensory feedback that will occur. Inverse models (controllers) generate the motor command that will cause a desired change in state, given an environmental context. During motor learning, the forward and inverse models are paired and tightly coupled by a responsibility signal within modules. Using the forward model\u2019s predictions and sensory contextual cues, responsibility signals indicate the degree to which each pair should be responsible for controlling current behavior.\n\n== Impairment of motor programs ==\n\n=== Cerebellar degeneration ===\n\nErrors in reaching are commonly found in patients with cerebellar degeneration. This suggests their motor commands do not predicatively compensate for interaction torques inherent in multi-joint motion.<ref name=\"Bastian 1996\">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Bastian | first1 = AJ. | last2 = Martin | first2 = TA. | last3 = Keating | first3 = JG. | last4 = Thach | first4 = WT. | title = Cerebellar ataxia: abnormal control of interaction torques across multiple joints. | journal = J Neurophysiol | volume = 76 | issue = 1 | pages = 492\u2013509 |date=Jul 1996 | pmid = 8836239 | doi = 10.1152/jn.1996.76.1.492 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/08c7cd2aad071252919514d792b7cf64a98a5ace }}</ref><ref name=\"Bastian 2000\">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Bastian | first1 = AJ. | last2 = Zackowski | first2 = KM. | last3 = Thach | first3 = WT. | title = Cerebellar ataxia: torque deficiency or torque mismatch between joints? | journal = J Neurophysiol | volume = 83 | issue = 5 | pages = 3019\u201330 |date=May 2000 | pmid = 10805697 | doi = 10.1152/jn.2000.83.5.3019 | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c86be191432db3abb56bf11c3050a7b62abeafcd }}</ref><ref name=\"Goodkin 1993\">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Goodkin | first1 = HP. | last2 = Keating | first2 = JG. | last3 = Martin | first3 = TA. | last4 = Thach | first4 = WT. | title = Preserved simple and impaired compound movement after infarction in the territory of the superior cerebellar artery. | journal = Can J Neurol Sci | volume = 20 Suppl 3 | issue =  | pages = S93\u2013104 |date=May 1993 | doi =  10.1017/s0317167100048599| pmid = 8334599 }}</ref><ref name=\"Topka 1998\">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Topka | first1 = H. | last2 = Konczak | first2 = J. | last3 = Schneider | first3 = K. | last4 = Boose | first4 = A. | last5 = Dichgans | first5 = J. | title = Multijoint arm movements in cerebellar ataxia: abnormal control of movement dynamics. | journal = Exp Brain Res | volume = 119 | issue = 4 | pages = 493\u2013503 |date=Apr 1998 | doi = 10.1007/s002210050365 | pmid = 9588784 }}</ref> Several lines of research have been conducted to understand this, with evidence being provided that this impairment may be due to a malfunctioning inverse model:\n* the cerebellum plays a dominant role in representing the inverse model<ref name=\"Kawato 1992\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kawato M, Gomi H |title=A computational model of four regions of the cerebellum based on feedback-error learning |journal=Biol Cybern |volume=68 |issue=2 |pages=95\u2013103 |year=1992 |pmid=1486143 |doi=10.1007/BF00201431 |url=}}</ref>\n* the cerebellum is active during learning of arm movements in force fields.<ref name=\"Nezafat 2001\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Nezafat R, Shadmehr R, Holcomb HH |title=Long-term adaptation to dynamics of reaching movements: a PET study |journal=Exp Brain Res |volume=140 |issue=1 |pages=66\u201376 |date=September 2001 |pmid=11500799 |doi=10.1007/s002210100787 |url=}}</ref>\n\nWith this knowledge, an experiment conducted by Smith and Shadmehr (2005)<ref name=\"Smith 2005\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Smith MA, Shadmehr R |title=Intact ability to learn internal models of arm dynamics in Huntington's disease but not cerebellar degeneration |journal=J. Neurophysiol. |volume=93 |issue=5 |pages=2809\u201321 |date=May 2005 |pmid=15625094 |doi=10.1152/jn.00943.2004 |url=|citeseerx=10.1.1.392.195 }}</ref> illustrated an impaired ability for cerebellar subjects to alter motor commands to compensate for applied force fields within a trial (i.e. modify an ongoing movement) as well as to use this error to update the following trial (i.e. changes in a following trial were unrelated to prior trial error). This agreed with prior work by Mascheke et al. (2004)<ref name=\"Maschke 2003\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Maschke M, Gomez CM, Ebner TJ, Konczak J |title=Hereditary cerebellar ataxia progressively impairs force adaptation during goal-directed arm movements |journal=J. Neurophysiol. |volume=91 |issue=1 |pages=230\u20138 |date=January 2004 |pmid=13679403 |doi=10.1152/jn.00557.2003 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/2415d3a19b241d4a2d3775d79ad20f4345d8534f}}</ref> who illustrated those with cerebellar degeneration had difficulty adapting motor commands when limb dynamics were altered.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Central pattern generator]]\n*[[Challenge Point Framework]]\n*[[Hearing (sense)|Hearing]]\n*[[Multisensory integration]]\n*[[Proprioception]]\n*[[Vestibular system]]\n*[[Visual perception]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading ==\n\n=== Sensory contributions to motor control ===\n# {{cite journal |author=Bastian AJ |title=Understanding sensorimotor adaptation and learning for rehabilitation |journal=Curr. Opin. Neurol. |volume=21 |issue=6 |pages=628\u201333 |date=December 2008 |pmid=18989103 |pmc=2954436 |doi=10.1097/WCO.0b013e328315a293 |url=}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Bent LR, McFadyen BJ, Inglis JT |title=Vestibular contributions during human locomotor tasks |journal=Exerc Sport Sci Rev |volume=33 |issue=3 |pages=107\u201313 |date=July 2005 |pmid=16006817 |doi= 10.1097/00003677-200507000-00002}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Chapman GJ, Hollands MA |title=Age-related differences in stepping performance during step cycle-related removal of vision |journal=Exp Brain Res |volume=174 |issue=4 |pages=613\u201321 |date=October 2006 |pmid=16733708 |doi=10.1007/s00221-006-0507-6 |url=}}\n# {{cite book | last1 = Elliott | first1 = D | title = Intermittent versus continuous control of manual aiming movements | editors = L Proteau; D Elliott | work = Vision and Motor Control. Advances in Psychology, Volume 85 |pages = 33\u201348| publisher = Elsevier Science & Technology |location = New York | year = 1992 | isbn = 9781281789396 |oclc = 742292994}} \n# {{Cite book  | last1 = Kandel | first1 = Eric R. | title = Principles of Neural Science | year = 2012 | publisher = McGraw-Hill | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-07-139011-8 | oclc = 795553723 }}\n# {{Cite book  | last1 = Latash | first1 = Mark L. | title = Neurophysiological basis of movement | year = 2008 | publisher = Human Kinetics | location = Champaign, IL | isbn = 978-0-7360-6367-8 | oclc =  175174377 }}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Perry SD, McIlroy WE, Maki BE |title=The role of plantar cutaneous mechanoreceptors in the control of compensatory stepping reactions evoked by unpredictable, multi-directional perturbation |journal=Brain Res. |volume=877 |issue=2 |pages=401\u20136 |date=September 2000 |pmid=10986360 |doi=10.1016/S0006-8993(00)02712-8 |url=}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Reynolds RF, Day BL |title=Visual guidance of the human foot during a step |journal=J. Physiol. |volume=569 |issue=Pt 2 |pages=677\u201384 |date=December 2005 |pmid=16179363 |pmc=1464243 |doi=10.1113/jphysiol.2005.095869 |url=}}\n\n=== Control of Movement ===\n#{{Cite book  | last1 = Schmidt | first1 = Richard A. | last2 = Lee | first2 = Timothy Donald | title = Motor control and learning : a behavioral emphasis | year = 2011 | publisher = Human Kinetics | location = Champaign, IL | isbn = 978-0-7360-7961-7 | oclc = 814261802}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Grillner S, Wall\u00e9n P, Saitoh K, Kozlov A, Robertson B |title=Neural bases of goal-directed locomotion in vertebrates--an overview |journal=Brain Res Rev |volume=57 |issue=1 |pages=2\u201312 |date=January 2008 |pmid=17916382 |doi=10.1016/j.brainresrev.2007.06.027 |url=}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Marder E, Calabrese RL |title=Principles of rhythmic motor pattern generation |journal=Physiol. Rev. |volume=76 |issue=3 |pages=687\u2013717 |date=July 1996 |pmid=8757786 |doi= 10.1152/physrev.1996.76.3.687|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/19008ec50b0d0bcff24438c9a0eb57f9e33f7a85 }}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Shik ML, Orlovski\u012d GN, Severin FV |title=[Locomotion of the mesencephalic cat evoked by pyramidal stimulation] |language=Russian |journal=Biofizika |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=127\u201335 |year=1968 |pmid=5660863 |doi= |url=}}\n\n'''Reflexive, Triggered, and Voluntary Movement'''\n#  {{cite book | last1 = Rothwell | first1 = John C. | title = Control of Human Voluntary Movement | publisher = Chapman & Hall | year = 1994 | location = London | isbn = 978-0412477003 |oclc = 613884041 }}\n\n'''Speed, Accuracy, Movement Complexity'''\n# {{cite journal|last1=Fitts|first1=Paul M.|title=The information capacity of the human motor system in controlling the amplitude of movement.|journal=Journal of Experimental Psychology: General| volume=121|issue=3|year=1992|pages=262\u2013269|doi=10.1037/0096-3445.121.3.262|pmid=1402698|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/35f693753e23f5cda54815a55871fadc62cf18b3}}\n# {{cite journal|last1=Hick|first1=W. E.|title=On the rate of gain of information|journal=Quarterly Journal of Experimental Psychology|volume=4| issue=1|year=1952| pages=11\u201326| doi=10.1080/17470215208416600|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ee7363ba39bfc3dd030844933375d7585c7c9b66}}\n# {{cite journal |vauthors=Dassonville P, Lewis SM, Foster HE, Ashe J |title=Choice and stimulus-response compatibility affect duration of response selection |journal=Brain Res Cogn Brain Res |volume=7 |issue=3 |pages=235\u201340 |date=January 1999 |pmid=9838139 |doi=10.1016/s0926-6410(98)00027-5}}\n# {{cite journal |author=Favilla M |title=Reaching movements: programming time course is independent of choice number |journal=NeuroReport |volume=7 |issue=15\u201317 |pages=2629\u201334 |date=November 1996 |pmid=8981436 |doi=10.1097/00001756-199611040-00044}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n[[Category:Motor system]]\n[[Category:Motor skills]]\n[[Category:Motor control]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_program"}
{"title_page": "1991\u201392 Albanian First Division", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition      = [[Albanian First Division]]\n| season           = 1991\u201392\n| winners          = [[KS Sopoti Librazhd|Sopoti]]\n| promoted         = {{ubl|[[KS Sopoti Librazhd|Sopoti]]|[[KS Pun\u00ebtori Patos|Pun\u00ebtori]]}}\n| relegated        = {{ubl|[[KF Memaliaj]]|[[KF Selenica]]}}\n| league topscorer = \n| biggest home win = \n| biggest away win = \n| highest scoring  = \n| matches          = \n| total goals      = \n| prevseason = [[1990\u201391 Albanian First Division|1990\u201391]]\n| nextseason = [[1992\u201393 Albanian First Division|1992\u201393]]\n}}\nThe '''1991\u201392 Albanian First Division''' (Albanian: ''Kategoria e Par\u00eb'') was the 45th season of a second-tier [[Association football]] league in [[Albania]].\n\nThe 2nd Division 1991/92, after the upheavals of 1991, takes on a new guise. The 24 participating teams are divided into two groups for the regular season, in which they only play the first round. In the second round, each group is split into four groups by geographical areas (North and South) with the teams retaining the points of the first phase: the winners of each group pass to the final knockout phase (from the quarterfinals to the final). [[KS Sopoti Librazhd|Sopoti Librazhd]] and [[KS Pun\u00ebtori Patos|Pun\u00ebtori Patos]] make it to the final, earning promotion to the 1st Division, with the first qualifying division champion on penalties. [[KF Memaliaj]] is relegated to the lower divisions, in which [[KF Selenica]] will also sink, which, relegated from the 1st Division, will not be accepted in the 2nd Division 1992/93. They will be replaced by two new clubs, the [[KF Amaro Divas|Amaro Divas Tirana]] and the [[KF Iliria|Iliria Fush\u00eb-Kruj\u00eb]].\n\n== First round ==\n=== Group A ===\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=PQ\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=BUR|name_BUR=[[KS Burreli|Burrel Mat]]\n|team2